Growing up as a Chinese immigrant, I constantly sought to balance assimilation with loyalty to my roots. 
    These two goals were often in conflict. At school, I was scared of showing any sense of incongruence, desperately trying to rid myself of my accent (a task I succeeded in), and suppressing numerous traditions that I felt made me too strange.
    And at home, it was a challenge maintaining friendships while keeping up with cultural and familial expectations. I too often found myself at odds with my parents over petty disagreements regarding time allocation for school versus socialization, and our lack of “normality” typical of American households made it difficult for me to relate to my peers.
    As such, I’ve never truly felt as if I belonged in one community, always in between. But, our ability to overcome challenges in life is the ultimate test of character, and, accordingly, during my sophomore year, I decided to overcome mine by starting a new club at school: the East Asian Student Union.
    The EASU is my proudest accomplishment in high school. We have been able to unite the countless stories just like mine of East Asian students on campus, while also showcasing our cultures to a wider audience, promoting a better understanding of our traditions. 
    It’s also given us the opportunity to speak on difficult societal issues, such as familial pressure and mental health, conflicts and false stereotypes surrounding East Asians, and the daily challenges we face as first and second generation immigrants.  
    For Westview’s East Asian community, I am a leader, and a bringer of change. I have helped to pave the way for a better future for my community on campus, and I hope to one day be able to do the same on a global stage.
